Class DishonestMap<K,V>

    public class DishonestMap<K,V>
extends ProxiedMap<K,V>
    A ProxiedMap which does nothing other than change the result of calls to Map.get(Object).

    The backing map's #get is first processed by the provided UnaryOperator before being passed to the caller.
    DishonestMap is useful for modifying returned values in a Map.
    Author:
    A248

    • Constructor Detail

      • DishonestMap

        public DishonestMap(Map<K,V> original,
                    UnaryOperator<V> processor)
        Creates a DishonestMap using the given map as the backing map and the UnaryOperator to process Map.get(Object) operations.

        When get(Object) is called, Function.apply(Object) is invoked on the results of original.get(key) where original is the backing map and key is the map key passed to #get

        For example, a map of unmodifiable maps could be created like so:
        Map<String, Map> mapOfUnmodifiableMaps = new DishonestMap<String, Map>(new HashMap<String, Map>, Collections::unmodifiableMap);
        Such a map would support all normal read and write operations, such as #put; however, its #get method would return an unmodifiable collection view (per Collections.unmodifiableMap(java.util.Map<? extends K, ? extends V>)) when called. (Essentially, the map's values would be unmodifiable maps, but the map as a whole would allow modification. For complete and total immutability use this example with UnmodifiableDishonestMap instead.

        Note that a reference is retained to the backing map. Changes to the backing map are reflected in the DishonestMap.
        Parameters:
        original - the original, backing map
        processor - with which to modify #get results
